##Where are all the people who left Wuhan before the city closed?

Vicechina  

Function description, different color vision

At 2 am on January 23, Wuhan announced that the airport and railway stations would be closed at 10 am on the same day, and the city's bus, subway, ferry and long-distance passenger services would also be suspended. "More than 5 million people have left Wuhan and 9 million remain in the city because of the Spring Festival and the epidemic, " said Zhou Xianwang, mayor of Wuhan, on the evening of June 26

According to an article by China Business News, based on big data, Wuhan, as a major province with an influx of migrants, has nearly half of its population leaving the city every year for the new year. Before Wuhan closed the city on January 10 and 22, between 60% and 70% of those who depart from Wuhan each day head to other cities in Hubei Province, followed by Henan, Hunan, Anhui, Chongqing and Jiangxi provinces.

But big data can't answer the question that most people want to know. Where is it? Who did you see? Why are you leaving? Why are you in my neighborhood? People keep asking questions, on the Internet, in the neighborhood, volume convergence, emotional complexity, people look around, eyes finally fell on the parking space in front of the building, from a row of plates in a panic to find a "e" word.

This year, each departure is no longer considered normal, and "leaving Wuhan" seems to have a natural moral flaw. Those who leave become the most ready-made defendants, and one after another mini-summons between the people is launched with irrefutable "justice" .

And for each tiny individual, the blamed outcast is as overwhelmed as the person who blamed them, holding his head up and making a momentary decision downstream of the message in order not to drown.

We interviewed several people who had "fled" Wuhan before the siege, piecing together a few atypical experiences that lasted more than a decade in some atypical responses. Personal Histories and diaries are especially valuable at a time when official voices can not be trusted, and the accounts of the three Chinese exiles are an honest indication of the beginning of the disaster.

Here's what the respondents said:

#

"My in-laws live in the 8 + 1 urban circle around Wuhan (a 100-kilometer radius of the city with Wuhan as the center) , and none of them have returned from Wuhan for the New Year. "

I usually in Wenzhou engaged in foreign trade work, once in Wuhan University, so myself and my daughter's Hukou are allowed to fall in Wuhan. On the 19th, I set off from Wenzhou with my daughter, planning to visit her in laws in rural Huanggang for the New Year, and to apply for her health insurance card as I passed through Wuhan. Everything went according to plan, and it all began with ignorance of the real epidemic.

I arrived in Wuhan on the morning of the 21st as planned, and began to hear about pneumonia. As early as the 18th, the Wuhan Hospital was already full and had to stand in line for 6-8 hours to see the fever clinic, according to the drivers of a gold and silver lake, but in contrast to the rumors, it was a relaxing scene on the streets of Wuhan. I remember, only about half of the people on the street were wearing face masks, government offices and banks went to work as usual, someone was taking their temperature at the gate of the office, the bank didn't, we were waiting in line at the bank to get our daughter's health insurance card, a staff member sent a couplet.

There was a long line at the bank, and I had a bad feeling about it, so I gave up on the insurance card and took off with the kids. That day, my two year old daughter began to have a cold and a fever. I didn't think it was pneumonia. I didn't dare take my child to the hospital. I bought Ibuprofen and Osse myself. The next day, the day before the city was shut down, my daughter's fever broke, and I drove my children out of Wuhan, up the National Highway, to my mother in Law's house in Huanggang.

In retrospect, I was told that there were no children on the sick list, so I didn't think my daughter was new. But in the face of endless lines and inhospitable hospitals, even if one person fled Wuhan because of doubts about his infection, I also feel that there is nothing morally wrong with him. I can now say that no one is a saint.

My in-laws live in Huanggang, part of the 8 + 1 City Circle Around Wuhan, where many of my fellow villagers deliver gas and do housework. Every Spring Festival, about 40 percent of the families welcome their families back from Wuhan. Even before academician Zhong Nanshan issued a warning on the 20th, many people were already on their way home, along with our sister in law who works in finance in Wuhan.

After returning home, for 14 days, the village road was closed, express delivery can not come in, masks can not buy, there is no convenience store in the countryside, the store's stock is only snacks. We stir-fry our yard food on a clay stove, touch the eggs laid by the chickens, and marinate the meat and fish to extend the shelf life. I made a bitter joke in the circle of friends, saying that I had lived a "life of being an internet celebrity. ". Ten days went by, and the aged, blackened oranges on the orange tree at our door were eaten up.

The vegetable patch and the orange tree in the yard

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The daughter was eating an old orange from a tree

From the 24th, the bus service in Xiaogan, also a city near Wuhan, where my family lives, was suspended. It and Huanggang, where I live, are the second and third most diagnosed people in Hubei Province, second only to Wuhan in severity, but far behind in terms of health care and public awareness. My family told me that the village fever did not go to see, confirmed no one disinfection, everywhere. Compared with Wuhan, its surrounding radiation to the city circle, as if in a public discourse in an invisible corner.

After so long, my emotions have shifted from worrying about the epidemic to worrying about the future. The House loan, the child, all needs the money, my enterprise starts on February 10, if not back in March, the enterprise will not re-recruit in the local? When I went home for the New Year on January 19th, I had no idea how the epidemic would change my life, but even now I don't know.

"everyone told me to hurry back to Wuhan, don't infect others, I also want to go back. "

In retrospect, I saw a lot of signs before the plague. First came the closure of the south China Seafood Market, but we were told that the reason was "hygiene is not up to standard, we have to stop business for rectification, " and then an article started circulating among friends, saying that the closure in south China was actually due to a virus, but a few days later, the rumor was that the person who wrote the article had been arrested. Then a doctor named Wang Guangfa said the virus could be prevented and controlled. Don't worry. After all these twists and turns, we were relieved to go on the trip as planned.

On January 19, my dad and I were on a Chinese international tour group to Taiwan. On the day we set off, things were going as usual in Wuhan. I distinctly remember that no one at the airport was wearing masks. A day or three after arriving in Taiwan, Taiwanese media reported that the doctor, Wang Guangfa, who claimed that pneumonia could be prevented and controlled, had been infected.

We were supposed to spend 10 days in Taiwan until the news of the siege came from Wuhan on the 23rd, when the party realized the severity of the epidemic. On the 25th, a Taiwanese businessman doing business in Wuhan was diagnosed as Xin Guan, and Taiwan issued an order to immediately repatriate all tour groups from Hubei.

On the 26th, due to the closure of Wuhan and Taiwan's refusal to let us stay, the tour guide bought the first flight out and flew to Shanghai Pudong International Airport. The tour guide told us that the tour group was only responsible for taking us back to the mainland, and that they couldn't tell us where to go or where to go when we landed.

When we landed at Pudong Airport, the staff of the airport docked us with the Shanghai Epidemic Prevention Bureau. The latter isolated us to the Guanhai Park Hotel in Nanhui Zui, Shanghai, saying that we should stay in Shanghai for 14 days before leaving. Originally to travel to Taiwan we only took short-sleeved shorts, no heating, but fortunately enough tube.

On February 2, a staff member suddenly sent me a wechat message, saying that to implement the new quarantine standards, you don't have to be quarantined in Shanghai for 14 days, as long as you don't get sick from the day you left Wuhan (the 19th) , you can leave the quarantine point. According to the new criteria, I had already met the conditions for de-quarantining, so I had to leave the hotel by 12 noon the next day.

My guess is that the number of suspected cases in Shanghai is also on the rise, causing a strain on the isolation rooms and prompting us to give them to those in need. But where would we go? The hotel outside the closed city of Wuhan refused to accept Wuhan people, and the staff simply said, since you can't go back to Wuhan, you can go somewhere else. Fellow villagers in the Wechat group asked, if half of the isolation will let us out free vagrancy, then the isolation of what is the point? My wechat group released Kunming directly with Wuhan Docking, to help stranded travelers in Wuhan anti-hometown policy, asked why Shanghai can not do, the result is removed from the group chat.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
I reflected on the problem on Weibo, many netizens said that I should not have come out in the first place, not to mention landing in Shanghai. I can understand, opaque information, one-size-fits-all policy, always end up with specific people paying the "necessary price, " only this time it's my turn to pay.

On February 5, the staff chartered a bus to take us to the nearest dishuihu subway station. We took the subway for two and a half hours to Shanghai Hongqiao Railway Station, first by train, then by black car. Black car met a lot of Wuhan fellow-townsman, most are in the field after being quarantined back home, very kind.

"That's when I realized it was happening to me, too. "

I work in Wuhan. On January 20, the company had a holiday. The next day, a friend drove back to his hometown of Xinyang. None of US expected it to turn out like this.

Four or five days after my return, I heard from my father that some of the Wuhan residents from our village had already been registered in the village. During my 14 days of isolation at home (January 21 to February 5) , the village made two house calls, checking information, asking about outings, similar home visits, which turned into phone calls, adding that the county and the city would also call.

But since then, in addition to the county and the city, there have been calls from unknown numbers, asking questions, "is it XX? Is it Wuhan? When did you come back? " At first I didn't care, later, I talked to my colleagues who had returned from Wuhan to Hunan, Shandong, Sichuan and other places, only to learn that their personal phone numbers, ID cards and residential addresses were also leaked. A colleague went home, was announced in the community of the owners of the group, he silently looked at himself to be talked about, a long time, suddenly someone asked, "they have a family in the group? "

That's when I realized it was happening to me, too, but where it came from, I don't know, with us, word gets around too fast.

Chat records of co-workers and community owners

Another colleague's information was put together on a public information sheet

Fortunately, by the end of the year, there will be few harassing phone calls. And my family in the countryside, parents are farmers, rice, oil and salt do not lack. To say inconvenient, that is, originally intended to return to Wuhan after the New Year, now no clothes, no computer with the company notice 17 back to Wuhan to work, I do not know how I will be.

What is difficult is the friend who brought me home by car. He is a civil servant in Wuhan. The unit urged him to go back and opened a letter to all departments in the county to let him pass, but the street took away his car parked in front of his house, saying that it was for centralized control. He went to see where the control was collected, most of them are cars with the letters "e" , and now that the traffic is blocked, he really can't go anywhere.

When the epidemic first broke out, someone used the "escaped Wuhan People" to cover the five million people who left Wuhan. "Wuhan People" from a specific reference, a specific image, at the same time as a "plague" carrier and alias. When a man is not considered a man, but only a "disease" , all injustice can be justified. We have to cut it off, isolate it, like a garbage dump in a corner of a community, to be able to handle it cleanly and cleanly.

In "A journey through the epidemic: Whispers of Malacca, " Xu said that in a disaster, "habitual actions" must be used at the grassroots level, the use of red tassels, red armbands, loudspeakers, and boldfaced slogans -- all of which are motivating and penetrating -- but at the same time, they are also violent, inflexible, and act for the sake of action, a psychological reflection of a zero sum society.

So, between zero and one, the Wuhan drifters, the people in need of treatment for other diseases, the old people who can't buy masks, the people who are isolated, driven away, ignored, eliminated, who are seen as integral, are rounded up to zero.
